 
Step‑by‑step: Build the KCD allow‑list (msDS‑AllowedToDelegateTo)
 
1) Identify the delegating (front‑end) identity
This is the account you will configure on the Delegation tab.
	• If the front‑end service runs as Local System / Network Service, the effective identity is the computer account (e.g., SERVER$).
	• If it runs under a domain user/service account (including gMSA), the delegating identity is that user/gMSA.
	 
2) Enable auditing on Domain Controllers to generate Event 4769
Configure the Domain Controllers to log Kerberos service ticket requests:
	• In the Domain Controllers OU policy, enable:
		○ Audit Kerberos Service Ticket Operations = Success and Failure
This produces Security Event ID 4769 on DCs.
		 
3) Collect events during representative “normal operation”
Have the application run through normal usage (including any batch/background workloads), then collect 4769 events over a representative window
 
4) Filter the DC Security log to the delegating identity and to successful tickets
This is the key step that produces the candidate allow‑list:
	• Filter Event ID 4769
	• Filter TargetUserName = your delegating identity
	• Filter Status = 0x0 (success)
Use Event Viewer:
	• Open Security log on a DC → Filter Current Log… → XML tab → Edit query manually
	 
5) XML query (paste as-is, then change the account value)
Replace xxx@xxx.xxx.xxx with your delegating account (user/gMSA or SERVER$ as applicable).
 
<QueryList>
 <Query Id="0" Path="Security">
   <Select Path="Security">
     *[System[(EventID=4769)]]
     and
     *[EventData[Data[@Name='TargetUserName']='xxx@xxx.xxx.xxx']]
     and
     *[EventData[Data[@Name='Status']='0x0']]
   </Select>
 </Query>
</QueryList>
 
Notes:
	• In Event 4769, the “Account Name” from the friendly view is stored as TargetUserName, and Status=0x0 indicates success.
	 
6) Extract and deduplicate the Service Name values
From the filtered successful 4769 results:
	• The Service Name field is the target SPN that was requested (your back‑end target).
	• Collect the distinct Service Name values (deduplicate them).
This set becomes your candidate allow‑list for KCD (msDS‑AllowedToDelegateTo).
	 
7) Treat failures separately (do not build the allow‑list from failures)
If you see failures (Status/Failure Code ≠ 0x0), use them for troubleshooting only:
	• Successful 4769 events (0x0) = definitive “what works” list for allow‑listing.
	• Failed 4769 events = “what is attempted but not issuing a ticket,” which usually requires fixing (for example, missing/incorrect SPN format or other blocking conditions).
8) Configure KCD using the candidate allow‑list
Once you have the deduplicated Service Name list from successful 4769 events:
	• Configure constrained delegation on the delegating (front‑end) identity.
	• Add only the required back‑end SPNs (the deduplicated Service Name values) to the allow‑list and then pilot the change.
